#===============================================================
# TEACHING MOMENT: .dockerignore vs. .gitignore
#
# .gitignore:
#   - Excludes files from version control (Git repository)
#   - Prevents committing secrets, build outputs
#   - Shared across all developers
#
# .dockerignore:
#   - Excludes files from Docker build context
#   - Reduces context size sent to Docker daemon
#   - Improves build performance
#
# KEY DIFFERENCE:
#   - .gitignore: "What should NOT be in Git"
#   - .dockerignore: "What should NOT be in Docker image"
#
# EXAMPLE:
#   - bin/obj/ in BOTH (build outputs not needed)
#   - appsettings.json in .dockerignore but NOT .gitignore
#     (config files committed to Git, but secrets injected at runtime)
#
#===============================================================
# PERFORMANCE IMPACT (Typical SymbolLabsForge Build):
#
# Without .dockerignore:
#   - Build context: ~800 MB (includes bin/, obj/, Assets/)
#   - Context upload time: ~15 seconds
#
# With .dockerignore:
#   - Build context: ~50 MB (source code only)
#   - Context upload time: ~2 seconds
#
# SAVINGS: 13 seconds per build (87% reduction)
#
#===============================================================
# SECURITY BEST PRACTICE:
#
# ALWAYS exclude:
#   - Secrets files (*.pfx, *.key, .env)
#   - Development configs (appsettings.Development.json)
#   - User-specific files (launchSettings.json)
#   - Credentials (AWS keys, Azure connection strings)
#
# WHY: These files can leak into image layers and be extracted
# by anyone with access to the image (even if deleted later).
#
# RULE: "If it's secret, it shouldn't be in the build context."
#
#===============================================================
